This general rule is (V. 21) that to take a thing from an- other man, or to cause another man any prejudice for our own advantage, is more repugnant to nature than death, poverty, pain, or other accidents to person or property; for it destroys human society itself. And this rule is sanctioned (23) by the civil law.

But it is still more plainly the dictate of the natural law3 for all the virtues (24, 25, 26) are evidently more iu harmony with nature than the corresponding vices. Thus the interest of the individual (VI) and that of the eommunity should be considered as identical; all are bound (27) by the same law of nature3 and we are no more excusable for violating the rights of a stranger or a felloweitizen (28) than those of mem·- bers of our own family.
